<br>
In a post 50 encounter, if a druid intends literally to tank the add, he is insane.  Regrowth and a DS are awesome, but they can't keep up with the damage dealt by a 53rd level Rock Golem for example.  A caster who consistently aggros mobs will drain a cleric's blue bar faster than you can blink.  At best, its a recipe for major down time.<br>
<br>
I have nothing wrong with a caster jumping up and hitting the mob a few times as long as they don't draw aggro.  Admittedly, the time might be better spend medding, but if they're having fun doing it why suck the life from the game.<br>
<br>
I also support a caster who wants to work up his defense --  as long as he  tells people what he's doing -- tanking a mob for a bit.  In the long run, the higher defense pays off for everyone.  But generally, this kind of improvement is better done in controlled, non experience group situations, i.e., find a blue mob, root it, and let the caster get beat up.<br>
<br>
Now, what I see druids doing in multiple mob situations where we don't have an enchanter is call out, I'll handle the add -- not tank it mind you, but handle it.  A good druid can root park and rot a mob or kite it without getting killed.<br>
<br>
We all have our strengths, we should play to them.<br>
